segments.text: by David White of Texas A&M University on April the 22nd, 1989, concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
That's fine with me, David.
All right.
And you are, of course, Tom Rugg.
You were born when?
May 5th of 1948.
So would you classify yourself a baby boomer then?
I think I'm right on baby boomer age, yeah.
And you were born where?
In Denver, Colorado.
Denver, Colorado.
Were you up there?
No, I didn't.
I grew up all over the country.
My dad was and still is in the oil business, in the engineering end of it.
And they seemed to think it important that you move periodically.
So we did.
So where did you end up spending your high school years?
My sophomore year in high school I spent in Wichita, Kansas.
My junior year in high school I spent in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma.
And my senior year in high school I spent in Hobbs, New Mexico.
New Mexico.
So you really weren't near any of the
What would be traditionally classified as the hot spots of the nation, like Berkeley or New York or any of those places?
No.
Now, what do you remember about Kennedy?
What was your first recollection of Kennedy?
You must have been 12 years old at the time.
Yeah, I guess my first recollections about Kennedy...
would have been at about age 12.

And I guess the strongest recollection and impression I have about John Kennedy was the fact that he was a Catholic, which my parents seemed to think, in the political scheme of things, was extremely important, they being Protestants.
They thought it was important in a negative sense.
So they were, in a sense, against Kennedy for that reason.
Well, my parents were and always have been very closely aligned with the Republican Party.
So John Kennedy being the nominee of the Democratic Party was not going to be their favorite son in any event.
But the fact that he was Catholic was very important.
And I remember from my own
personal perspectives at that age that he was a very impressive figure.
I thought his accent was a little strange and the way he said words was funny, but I still think that about Massachusetts people.
I see.
Now, you mentioned your parents were Republican.
Would that say they were conservative?
Yes, I would classify them as conservatives then and now.
Were you, to an extent, influenced by your parents' views, or were you...
offset by it?
Yeah, I think it probably went the other way.
Certainly, pre-teenager, I was influenced by their views.
But as I reached teenage status and on towards adulthood, I think I became much more rebellious in my attitude toward my parents.
in my views today are in a lot of respects very much opposed to the kinds of conservative traditional political views that they held and still hold.
What do you think was the major turning point during your pre-teen high school years that sort of made you turn away from your parents' conservative views?
I'm not sure I can pinpoint.
any one thing.
It may be a part of just the natural growing up process that all adolescents go through.
The desire and want to be independent and the need to develop and assert your own identity is inherently inconsistent with adopting parental views.
But I can't pinpoint any single event or period of time.
when I became more rebellious towards my parents.
Would you have classified yourself as an interested teenager?
Meaning that, did you keep up to date with world events and national events and such?
Oh, yeah.
That was something that seemed to just naturally be a part of whatever group I was with of peers.
Those were important events to the people that I ran with, and I guess so far as I knew, although I would have had no way to know different, they were important to everybody.
Do you remember watching any of the civil rights marches on television?
Oh, yeah.
Very much so.
What were your impressions?
I guess you get a little different perspective about the civil rights movement when you're not stuck in any one place.
Let's pause this thing for just a minute.
So we were talking about civil rights.
Continue, please.
Yeah, for example, you got different views from different parts of the country.
Wichita, Kansas was a very interesting town and was then
very racially polarized.

The part of Oklahoma City when I was in my junior year in high school that I was familiar with was not, although I do have some very distinct remembrances and impressions about the first black students to come to the high school when I was there.
And then Hobbs, New Mexico, there was a one high school town, a much smaller community,
And the community attitude was, you know, black people were black and white people were white.
Nobody paid it much attention.
It wasn't a big issue.
So depending on where you were, that was the kind of backgrounds you were being exposed to.
And I think my attitude was one kind of amusement.
I never really...
understood how you could form any definite opinions or attitudes about people based solely on their appearance or the color of their skin.
And I don't know where that attitude came from.
Certainly not necessarily a traditional conservative attitude.
So would you say that growing up in that, going to school in that one high school town sort of helped to
solidify your views on race relations, just to the point where it doesn't matter?

Yeah, I think that was a, certainly of the communities that I grew up in, that was far and away the best community in terms of not having racial tension or racial issues be important, and that's a much more comfortable atmosphere to live in.
What do you think about Kennedy's
attitude towards civil rights?
Well, I don't know.
I guess I thought, you know, at that point in time, I'd never lived in the South, the Deep South, which seemed to be the focus of an awful lot of the racial problems.
The big cities seemed to be the other focus outside of the South.
And I guess it sort of seemed like to me that
that his approach to racial issues, at least as I understood it, one of equality fit with my idea of what America was all about.
I guess I agreed with him.
I never really had much of a problem with it.
You mentioned what America was all about.
What was America all about?
Well, to me, America was all about everybody gets an even shot and a fair shake and right wins and wrong loses.

pretty idealistic attitude, I guess, but I think it's a right one and one, I think, that still prevails is my attitude about America, although I've learned that for right to prevail can be a long and hard struggle and doesn't happen overnight.
I see that.
He said everyone deserved an even shot and a fair shake.

Yeah, and I thought that America was designed to give that opportunity to people, and I think still does in the overall generic sense, although in individual cases there are certainly going to be sharp contrasts and differences and opportunities if you focus on the individual.
But if you look at the country as a whole,
As a general rule, a person's ability to achieve and succeed and be happy generally depends on individual choices that an individual is more or less free to make.
You know, there are some outside constraints on choices that may be reflected or affected by background or community or things of that nature.
But in the overall sense, as a big picture, basically the choices you make dictate the happiness you have.
Did you think at the time that everyone should have this all over the world or just Americans?
I never really thought much in terms of world politics and still don't, I guess.
I know I went through a period of time where it seemed like to me the type of government, the name you hang upon on a particular type of government probably wasn't all that important.
But if it was, it was in another place far removed from anything that I cared much about.
in a lot of ways characterized my attitude about the Vietnam War.
You know, it's halfway around the world.
I figured those people had a right to self-determination.
They ought to work it out themselves.
When was the first time you remember hearing about Vietnam?
I can't remember the first time.
Obviously it was in high school because we had the draft in those days.
And
people of draft age were being sent to Vietnam, and they were fighting there, and they were dying.
And that was true in the early 60s and became much more true in the later 60s as I approached draft age and graduation from high school.
And I know at some point in time in there, it was probably the single most important topic that young men talked about.
So you would classify your feelings in high school
concerned but apathetic?
I was apathetic towards Vietnam as a country.
I think I still am.
It doesn't matter to me whether Vietnam is under the influence of a communist form of government.
or a populist form of government or a democratic form of government, I don't care.
It just doesn't matter to me.
It seems to me that that's a problem for the people who live in Vietnam to solve their own way in whatever way it takes to solve that.
I don't think it's any of my business to intervene or interfere in that.
So that was my attitude about Vietnam as a country and as a people.
My attitude about U.S. involvement in Vietnam was very much different because that was very personal
and was becoming more and more personal as time went by because it had a significant possibility of affecting me directly.
Would you say at the time you had a great fear of death?

Well, let's say that I certainly wasn't looking forward to ending my life on a premature basis, although I think like many teenage boys, occasionally I did some things that would make you wonder if I really believed that.
But as a general proposition, death was sort of an unknown thing and something that I thought should happen to old people and not young people.
I still think that's true.
Did you know personally anyone in high school that was drafted before you graduated, say someone from the class or two ahead of you?
Now that was, I guess that was one of the things I was insulated from because in three years I was in three different cities in three different states.
I lost track of the older people.
And I have an older sister who's two and a half years older than me, so she was far enough removed that her friends were not people that I really knew.
You know, being two years apart in high school is like a lifetime away from each other.

So no, I didn't, at the time I registered for the draft, the people I knew who were registered for the draft and being drafted were my peers, people the summer I came out of high school were the people I knew who were being drafted.
Now, so you...
You were of draft status.
Let me ask to put it to you this way.
What was your draft status when you left high school?
I believe they called it 1A back in those days.
You were the hot number.
You knew that when you got out of high school that the odds are you were going to be called up.
Sure.
Well, you didn't know what the odds were in those days, but you were certainly a draft status eligible student.
And for a combination of reasons, college student deferments were very much available in the early 60s.
And by the time, as were married deferments in the early 60s, if you were married, they wouldn't draft you.
As we reached the mid-60s, and I graduated in 1966, suddenly student deferments became very elusive for some people.
And married deferment by then had been dropped altogether.
So there were a number of things.
you could do to try to go on with your life that didn't guarantee your life wasn't going to be interrupted by a call from the Selective Service System and you entering the military.
So you were 1A when you got out of high school?
I was 1A when I got out of high school.
What were your thoughts when you got out of high school?
Were you planning on going to college?
Oh, I went to college immediately.
I started the summer
but I graduated from high school and went directly into college.
Where was that?
At New Mexico State University.
And so you had a 2S deferment?
No, I did not.
I was never able to quite put a handle on why it was my draft board refused me a student deferment status, but they did, and I was never 2S throughout the existence of the draft.
It was a rather strange set of circumstances.
I always suspected that
because I had registered late for the draft, that perhaps I had gotten a special flag on my record.
But at any rate, I applied for and was denied student deferment status.
Was there any particular reason why you registered late?
Well, at that point in time, I know that I was very reluctant to register for the draft.
I had formulated a definite opinion by that point in time that the war in Vietnam was wrong for America, probably wrong generally, but wrong for me personally.
My father made me register for the draft.
He was right.
It was the law.
I needed to do it.
So I was late.
While you were going to school at New Mexico State, you were still in danger of being drafted.
Oh, absolutely.
And at the end of my second semester, they tried to draft me.
What happened?
Well, the first effort they made at drafting me, I got a letter in the mail and decided that maybe New Mexico wasn't such a good place to be.
My folks had moved to Beaumont, Texas by then, and
I thought it would be a good time to visit, so I did.
Did you withdraw from school?
No.
I visited down here and contacted the local draft board here to have them transfer my draft papers from Lovington, New Mexico to Beaumont, Texas.
They started without question, started the paperwork, the wheels in motion,
whatever government forms they had to fill out, they filled those out and fired them off.
I told them I was going to be a permanent resident here.
Very shortly after that, I was only here a couple of weeks, I went back to New Mexico State University.
And by moving back and forth, just simply attempted to have the Selective Service System lose Tom Ruck.
They did for a period of time.
After
And I forget what it was.
It was a month or two.

They found me through my grandmother Rugg in Denver, Colorado, who's now deceased, who called my parents in Beaumont who were in a panic wanting, grandmother was in a panic wanting to know why the Army was looking for me.
I wasn't in the Army.
And called my parents in Beaumont.
And my dad turned the tide again.
and told me that basically this wasn't the way you played the game with these folks.
You could end up in prison doing this kind of stuff.
And I actually underwent a pre-induction physical for the military in El Paso sometime during my third semester, which would have been the spring of 67.
You went into your physical.
Yeah, I flunked the physical.
That was the only good thing that happened to me.
In my experiences with the military,
I ran across some military doctors, and apparently these guys had a tremendous attitude.
You can't believe this, knowing that probably half the guys who were there for their pre-induction physical, or maybe more, were there basically against their will and desires.
These guys acted like I was going to have some tremendous disappointment if they didn't pass me on my physical and let me into the military.
I had an acne condition.
that had, as many teenagers do, and it was on my chest and arms.
And they decided that military clothing would aggravate that condition.
I thought just the style of military clothing was going to aggravate my attitude.
But they decided to give me a medical deferment for one year.
It was called a one-wide deferment.
And they gave me a one-wide deferment.
from the military.
So for about a year or so you were basically off scot-free?
Yeah, the deal was you were supposed to go back after the end of the year, they'd send you a notice, you'd come back and take a physical again and they'd decide if you were fit to go at that point.
Well, I moved to Beaumont again.
At the end of that spring semester, a combination of events, I really had to move to Beaumont again.
The school had found out that my parents
No longer lived in New Mexico, therefore I managed to attain non-resident status.
And the tuition went up, obviously.
The tuition increase was staggering, and I couldn't afford school there, so I came to Beaumont.
Got a job and went to work.
Had my papers transferred again back to the Beaumont draft board, and went to work for
That summer and the next school fall semester, I entered Lamar the semester after that.
You said the other guys at the draft board were generally not in a mood to be going to the draft board and saying, hey, I want to come in?
Oh, the guys that were there for the physicals?
Yes.
Oh, yeah.
Of course, you always have and you always will have
I suppose you always will have, the people who are really gung-ho military types.
And they're fine.
Everybody's got to do their own thing.
It'd be dull as hell if we were all alike.
And you had those kind there who were not students, had graduated from high school, and were looking for a place to go, and they were going to land in the military.
But you had a lot of students or people who had flunked out of college, people
who were not terribly interested in the military, who were also there for their physicals.
You know, you had some conversations with the people in your close physical area.
I mean, they must have run through 200 at a time.
But you had some conversations with people on, hey, who are you, why are you here, that kind of thing.
Enough to know that I wasn't the only person there who didn't want to be.

Would you characterize their feelings as just general, I don't want to go over there and die, or were they specifically saying what we're doing is wrong, I don't want to go, I'm a conscientious objector, that sort of thing?
No, I think there was a lot of, you had a lot of the people who it was really more of a fear and apprehension of the prospect of going and getting in a war and getting shot at and killed.
The really
strong, true, conscientious objectors I don't think ever saw the pre-induction physical process.
I think a lot of those people ended up in other countries, if the draft board could ever run them down.
This is a bit off the subject, but you were, being in El Paso, you were close to Mexico.
Did the thought ever occur to you of maybe going over to Mexico and hanging out for a while?
No, the thought occurred to me to go to Canada.

economic situation in Canada is a little bit more conducive than it is in Mexico, plus your chances of speaking, running into people who speak the English language who are natives of Canada are significantly higher.
And then there were rumors going on then that if you went to Mexico and got caught, it wouldn't do you any good because the Mexicans would just send you back anyway, and that the Canadians wouldn't.
Now, whether or not any of that was true or not wasn't as important as what you believe was true.
So Canada was a consideration, just depending on how this draft thing went.
I did know that if I passed the pre-induction physical, they weren't going to force me to stay on the base.
I would have an opportunity to leave and be expected to come back.
So I had some time to work with formulating a final plan.
An escape hatch, as it were.
Yeah, I had a way out if it got to that.
Did you have one in mind when they told you to come on to the base?
Suppose they had not given you the one Y that day, what was your immediate option?
Well, I was really looking at a couple of options.
All of them involved leaving, which would have been fairly easy for me to do then.
I had a car and I could get everything I owned in the car and was used to traveling.
It wasn't any
any real problem for me to hop into a car and just take off.
I could certainly have done that.
I didn't really want to do that.
I had lots of friends in school, and I really wanted to stay in school and work on my education at that point in time.
So I didn't have any final battle plans.
I was just kind of going along.
You know the thing that's really scary about all that, now that I'm nearly 41, is I'm afraid that if I'd have passed the physical,

the absence of a real defined plan and a thing to do, I may have just followed along like sheep to the slaughter, which is the feeling I get happen to a lot of people who didn't want to be there and ended up going just because they didn't have any other alternatives that they were ready to pursue.
I think I've jumped ahead a little bit.
Do you mind if I backtrack a little?
No, not at all.
We've gotten as far as your years of
getting into the draft to 68.
I want to backtrack a little bit to 64.
OK. What was your first memory of LBJ?
Oh, I guess being sworn in as president after Kennedy's assassination.
See, I wasn't a Texan then.
The last time I'd lived in Texas, I was too young to remember.
And I'd lived out in Kermit and McKamey, way out in West Texas.
That's before I even went to school as a toddler.
So LBJ didn't mean anything to me.
I do remember the swearing-in ceremony, but I had no real impressions or knowledge of him or his politics or anything else about him.
Now, that changed as you got older, I take it.

Yeah, it became fairly obvious that for one reason or another, whether he was making the choices or his advisors were convincing him it was the right thing to do, that Vietnam had gone from a fairly minor skirmish out in the woods somewhere to a major full-blown war that they were trying to call a police action.
Things just got totally out of hand under his leadership or lack of leadership, whichever way that really went.
Do you remember any of the specific military operations being discussed in the news, like their announcing of the bombings, Rolling Thunder, stuff like that?
Yeah, I have some dim memories of that kind of stuff, of the bombings of Hanoi and North Vietnam in general.
unauthorized raids into Cambodia and Laos, places where they weren't supposed to be.
I had never had any doubt in my mind of the military's capability to do things they weren't supposed to do.
I never, in any sense, doubted the truthfulness of any of those stories.
Of course, I was a detractor from the war effort anyway, or a non-supporter, I guess.
So anything bad coming out of Vietnam in the way of news, I believed instantly without any real critical analysis.
Before the time you graduated high school, had any thoughts crossed your head of maybe going out and protesting or doing something active?
No, and that may have been, nobody was doing that in Hobbs, New Mexico.
What about Oklahoma City?
It really hadn't gotten to that level in Oklahoma City, at least not in my age group, which would have been high school junior.
High school senior certainly would have had some possibilities the way the war was developing by that point in time, but not in a town of 20,000 people with one high school.
That's just not the sort of thing that those size communities lend themselves to.
Now, is New Mexico State located in Hobbs, or is it located in... No, it's in Las Cruces.
Las Cruces.
Which is several hundred miles away in another very small town.
What was the student atmosphere like at New Mexico State, your first fall or spring semester there?
Well, the first semester there was summer school, which is, as I'm sure you know, isn't any real impression of what a campus and a university is really like.
So the first real semester would have been the fall semester.

of 66 and New Mexico State University then was primarily an engineering school and I don't guess it still is but a very serious studious type of student body and not one really given much to protesting at that point in time.
Although one wouldn't have described Lamar University then as one either and we had some dandy protests.
So you'd say that, by and large, these people were wrapped up in their studies.
Yeah, and I think a part of that was probably as much the time as anything else.
The real serious war protest movement was starting in other places and was going to take a while to filter down to some of your smaller campuses and universities.
What was the first major college protest you remember?
I remember Kent State, but I can't tell you when it even happened.
It's really odd.
You know, that was a big deal.
So you don't remember hearing about anything like that while you were at New Mexico State?
No, I don't remember there being any big protests at New Mexico State.
Not the three semesters that I was there.
So then you came to Beaumont and began working.
What was the attitude like in Beaumont at the time?
I know it's a town that would be classified as part of the old south, but... Yeah, and I don't know that I can even tell you.
You know, when the first time you hit a town to live, you're 19 years old, it's pretty difficult to get oriented.
You don't have a group to go into.
You're not going to school.
I lived here the first summer with my parents, and then they moved off again in the ongoing pursuit of never moving.
It was a part of my dad's profession.
And I don't know that I had a sense of what was going on in Beaumont.
I was pretty wrapped up in my own deal.
As soon as I was sure that I'd lost the draft board and that they really weren't going to try to find me and drag me off kicking and screaming out of the night from my apartment,
I was pretty secure with most of that.
Went on about trying to get my own life ordered.
So you went to work, and then you ended up enrolling at Lamar.
Yeah, I enrolled at Lamar.
Let's see, this would have been the spring semester of 68, I guess.
Those were funny times.
What was it like at Lamar back in spring 68?
You know, I don't know that I have any real hard, specific things that I can remember that would give me a sense of it all.
I lived on campus, which made me one of the unusual folks for Lamar, as opposed to New Mexico State, where the only place you could live was on campus.
And that's just because there wasn't any other housing available, basically.
There was a little bit, but 90% of the student body lived on campus.
At Lamar, it was completely reversed.
So there were people, the people that I knew were a pretty small part of the campus, and those were the folks who lived on campus.
I don't know, I suppose things were crazy at Lamar like they were everywhere else back in 68.
People going between studies, having a good time, and being worried about the wars and things like that.
Let me backtrack a bit for a sec.
You said 90% of the students at NMSU lived on campus, so you were in the dorms.
Yeah.
Did y'all ever get together and rap about your draft statuses, for example?
Yeah, I guess that's when I, certainly New Mexico State's when I found out that everybody up in New Mexico State except me, so far as I knew, everybody had a student deferment.
And I couldn't get one and didn't understand why.
My draft board would not tell me why.
And it was, you know, it was kind of hard to understand how I managed to achieve the exalted status of being singled out for special treatment.
But sure, we talked about it.
The guys with student affirmants didn't worry about the war.
Because as long as student deferments were generally available, and particularly as long as you as an individual had one, you didn't have to worry too much about the war.
So they were just relatively unconcerned?
Oh, I wouldn't say unconcerned.
They weren't as concerned as those people who did not have student deferments.
There weren't many of us out there at New Mexico State University.
Certainly there were some others.
Do you remember if they were planning on going into the fields that you would construe as being part of the war effort?
Oh, no.
Not that I was aware of.
I just keep getting the classic picture of the Dow recruiters and people throwing eggs and oranges at them, and I was wondering, did anything like that happen at New Mexico State?
No, not that I know of.
And that's a part of, you know, I was a freshman in the Mexico State.
There wasn't anybody recruiting that I ran with.
But I can't remember.
I know there were some people who were kind of working towards aeronautics and aerospace types of degrees.
but I don't really remember anybody being sought after for the war effort, although I'm reasonably certain back in those days they were bound to have had their recruiting effort.
I just can't remember who the main recruiters were at New Mexico State because I never went through that process.
Back to Lamar.
So you finished, you enrolled in Lamar in the spring of 1968.
Yeah, spring semester, right.
And it was fairly quiet for you, getting back with your studies?
Yeah, it was.
I can't remember really where the demonstrations and stuff started out at Lamar, but I know most of those were racially oriented, which I always thought was kind of amusing anyway.
Given my attitude toward racial issues and real lack of understanding of the Deep South, this was the first time in my life I'd lived this close to
It was the only time in my life I can ever remember living in an area where people thought it was really important that blacks and whites not swim in the same pool.
That was a new one on me.
That attitude about segregation, I had never run across that before.
That was just amazing.
Which is not to say that attitude wasn't in some other places.
I just wasn't aware of it.
But I thought a lot of folks like that were strong.
So the biggest concern down here was racial issues?
Seemed to be.
See, we don't go too much longer before I get lost in the war effort.
I can't remember when the lottery came out.
The military never called me back for a follow-up physical.
And at some point in time, I just can't remember.
It seems like maybe it was 69 or maybe 70 when they started the lottery system.

The lottery system, of course, the deal on the lottery system was nobody was going to have student deferments anymore, and everybody, you know, you were all going to go based on numbers, and they were going to draft certain age groups and this thing.
And it was very, very tumultuous around the dorms during that period of time just because of the unknowns of what was going to happen.
And I remember
when they had the lottery.
I didn't actually go watch it on TV.
I was doing something else.
But I remember my number was 364 and my roommate's number was 365.
And we spent weeks having water balloons tossed in our windows and being harassed and ridiculed by people with really exciting numbers like 19.
Numbers like that.
And the people who'd
whose lottery numbers had come out in the under 100 were just, you know, they thought life was at an end.
And for the rest of us, the war was over so far as we were.
I figured at 364 they'd take women and children first before they got around to me.
How did that work?
Was that once a week they'd call up the numbers in order?
What happened was when you registered for the draft from then on, you were assigned a number.
everybody in the Selective Service System was assigned a number randomly.
It's sort of the famous ping-pong ball system.
Here's a date.
This date gets X number.
May 5th got 364.
Then they would draft beginning at number one, and they'd call as many numbers as they needed to draft people for whatever time slot they thought was important.
And I don't know if the military or selective service was doing it on a weekly or a monthly basis.
But it was anticipated that they, in any given year, would go through 100 or 150.
Of course, then for the next year, you'd have a whole new crop of 18, 19-year-olds registering for the draft who'd get their numbers.
And the idea was ultimately just to draft them.
18, 19-year-olds for the draft because us older folks were so difficult to manage.
So by the time you turned 20, you were relatively in the clear.
Well, no, because when I turned 20, that system wasn't in place yet.
I was in the anything-go system and hung out there and couldn't get a student deferment.
The only thing saving my skin was a 1Y, and nobody called me to go back to the doctor to be examined again.
But the good thing about the lottery, once you got your number you had to serve one year of eligibility.
I served a year of eligibility with the number 364 knowing that there's no way in the world they're going to draft me.
And then after that I was reclassified 4F by the Selective Service who apparently decided that
Above all else, it was important that they get the final word in on Tom Rugg.
And since I had been classified 1Y, so far as they were concerned, and had served one year of eligibility, never understood that, how you could not be eligible and ineligible at the same time.
But it was just all a part of what I call military logic.
The terms don't really mesh well together.
But they did that, classified me 4F.
I appealed that.
Why?
I didn't want to be 4F.
